<font color="#FF0000">SERENITY...</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb  5  0:43:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I bought the book &quot;The Wall&quot;... in it the editor explains the monument and it's design.  It is a stark black chevron cut across a large patch of unbroken serene landscape.  In this it symbolizes the division the war caused within the country. The mirror polish of the surface is intended to allow the viewer to see themselves and their companion in the wall, to serve as a reflection into themselves on their feelings on the war and reflection of the men who died there.<br>
 <br>
There was no plan for a statue in the original design, the monument was designed to be a memorial within ourselves.  Our own statues could be erected in our minds... with our friends/relatives/comrades faces on them instead of people we never knew.  <br>
 <br>
The whole design was intended to be one of intense simplicity, (stark contrast to the war and issues surrounding it.)<br>
 <br>
The black of the marble was chosen to symbolize the night..<br>
 <br>
That's all I can remember of what was said about the design.<br>
 <br>
All I can say is that for me, it does the job... I have been there about 30 or so times.. (I used to live near Washington) and judging from not only my reaction, but the reaction of those there... it does exactly what Maya intended...<br>
 <br>
It makes you think...<br>

